\begin_layout Standard
In the submitted article, entitled 
\series bold

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Pseudo-potentials for hybridized carbon atoms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\series default
, we develop a new kind of pseudo-potentials for hybridized atoms.
 We focus on sp
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 carbon atoms and the properties of polyenes and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon
s.
 We show that the use of these potentials does not deteriorate the performance
 of the ab-initio methods we used, namely TD-DFT with 5 functionals and
 TD-HF, CASSCF, CASPT2.
 The differences we obtain between all electron and pseudo-potential calculation
s are 0.8 pm on geometrical parameters, 1.8 kcal /mol on a -27.1 kcal/mol reaction
 energy and a minimum average error of 0.2 eV on excitation energies and
 ionization potentials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We think, this work is in line with aims and scope of the Journal of Computation
al Chemistry.
\end_layout

